title: For Sale:  CZ75 Clone Tri Star L120 9mm 18 shot with 2 Mec-Gar 17 Shot Magazines Black Alloy Commander Hammer 4 1/2 inch 3 Dot NIB EAA Witness Competitor CZ Mag Compatible
postcontent:
Our # HG85040

This isn’t a CZ75, but it’s awfully close. Where the CZ75 is all steel and pretty heavy, This L120’s alloy frame renders the gross vehicle weight down from the CZ’s 34 ounces, to 28 ounces empty. Turkish guns are here to stay, and this one is remarkably well executed. It will be a strong, perhaps even fatal, competitor to EAA’s Witness series, because the Witnesses we’ve had will not accept CZ75 magazines. Its price competition to both Baby Eagles and parent CZs themselves will at least make ripples in the market. Design, of course, descends from John M. Browning’s 1935 Hi-Power. Manufacturer is Samsun Yurt Savunma Sanayi ve Ticaret A.S., simply SYS, of Canik, or Janik, Republic of Turkey. Importer is Tri Star of North KC, MO. Type is traditional single and double action blowback semi-automatic. Construction is steel barrel, slide, and internal parts all on a lightweight alloy frame. Barrel is 4 1/2 inch 6 groove, with pressed in barrel bushing. Slide to frame fit is excellent, with full contact rail that runs the length of the frame. Sights are classic CZ style three dot configuration, dovetailed rear sight and rivet secured modified partridge front, 6 1/2 inch sight radius with serrated rib on the slide. Hammer is .212 serrated skeleton Commander type, with .312 smooth face combat trigger. Double action pull is hitchy from a resting hammer, but smooth and consistent from the half cock position. Single action pull on the photo specimen measured 6 pounds with moderate felt creep. This pistol has a firing pin safety and main safety for right handed shooters. Lever safety will engage in all three hammer positions: full rest, half cock, and fully cocked for secure carry and single action cocked-and-locked readiness. Trigger guard configuration is SP01 type square serrated front face, and the grip frame is serrated fore and aft. Grip panels are hard grainy polymer with the T Tri Star logo. Magazines furnished are Mec-Gar CZ7517B, not catalogued but produced for Tri-Star exclusively in a bright blue finish. This is an excellent pistol. Fit and finish are excellent. Similar pistols from the parent CZ manufacturer command pricing upwards of $700 apiece. While we expect substantial price increases, we’re nevertheless offering the Tri Star / Canik 55 L120 in the photos, or one of its identical mates, for only $ 319.00. Not transferable to civilian residents of California, District of Colombia, Maryland, or Massachusetts. For civilian buyers in jurisdictions where 17 round magazines are restricted, we will sub 10 round Baby Eagle [or used 15 round CZ75] magazines for $10 per mag extra, $20 extra for 2 mag sub, or $30 off with no magazines. Affected jurisdictions include Aurora IL, Chicago Cook County IL, Colorado, Connecticut, Hawaii, New Jersey, New York, and South Bend, IN.

title: For Sale:  CZ75 Clone Tri Star T100 9mm 16 shot with 2 Mec-Gar 15 Shot Magazines Hard Chrome Satin Nickel type with Commander Hammer 3 7/8 inch 3 Dot NIB EAA Witness Competitor CZ Mag Compatible
postcontent:
Our # HG85110

This isn’t a CZ75 Compact. Where the CZ75 is all steel and pretty heavy, This T100’s alloy frame renders the gross vehicle weight down from a full size CZ’s 34 ounces, to 25 3/8 ounces empty. Turkish guns are here to stay, and this one is remarkably well executed. It will be a strong, perhaps even fatal, competitor to EAA’s Witness series, because the Witnesses we’ve had will not accept CZ75 magazines. Its price competition to both Baby Eagles and parent CZs themselves will at least make ripples in the market. Design, of course, descends from John M. Browning’s 1935 Hi-Power. Manufacturer is Samsun Yurt Savunma Sanayi ve Ticaret A.S., simply SYS, of Canik, or Janik, Republic of Turkey. Importer is Tri Star of North KC, MO. Type is traditional single and double action blowback semi-automatic. Construction is steel barrel, slide, and internal parts all on a lightweight alloy frame. Finish is Hard Chrome, very much like a Satin Nickel finish. Barrel is 3 7/8 inch 6 groove, with full length steel guide rod and pressed in barrel bushing. Slide to frame fit is excellent, with full contact rail that runs the length of the frame. Sights are Italian LPA combat three dot configuration, dovetailed rear sight and rivet secured modified partridge front, 5 1/4 inch sight radius with serrated rib on the slide. Hammer is .212 black matte steel serrated skeleton Commander type, with .312 smooth face matching combat trigger. Double action pull is hitchy from a resting hammer, but smooth and consistent from the half cock position. Single action pull on the photo specimen measured 6 pounds with moderate felt creep. This pistol has a firing pin safety and main safety for right handed shooters. Lever safety will engage in all three hammer positions: full rest, half cock, and fully cocked for secure carry and single action cocked-and-locked readiness. Trigger guard configuration is SP01 type square serrated front face, and the grip frame is serrated fore and aft. Grip panels are hard grainy polymer with the T Tri Star logo. Magazines furnished are Mec-Gar CZ7515B, not catalogued but produced for Tri-Star exclusively in a bright blue finish. This is an excellent pistol. Fit and finish are excellent. Similar pistols from the parent CZ manufacturer command pricing upwards of $700 apiece. title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson 469 669 Grips Factory S&W Logo Textured Pebble Unfired 16538 variant of 16539 Old Stock Unfired
postcontent:
Our # GR16538

Here are long discontinued Factory Grips for two and only two very popular variants of the Smith & Wesson Mini Series 9mm Compact Pistols, models 469 and 669. Manufacturer was Smith & Wesson of Springfield, MA. We have arbitrarily assigned an educated guess as to these grips’s sku; the checkered finish variants were 165390000, so we put 165380000 on these. Construction is molded hard black polymer. Finish is stippled or pebbled type, perhaps not as good looking as the checkered ones, but surer gripping. Factory logo is molded into the upper portion of each panel, as the photos show. The Smith & Wesson model 469 was manufactured from 1983 until 1988; and its companion stainless 669 only from 1985 until 1988. These grips will not fit any other pistol besides a Smith & Wesson model 469 or model 669, chambered in 9mm. Installation requires removal of the mainspring housing off the back of the grip frame, careful insertion, and reinstallation of the housing. Thanks to Mr. Lawrence Furlette for his 2010 you tube video of the process, that one’s easy to find. If you’re not sure how to do it, don’t be a dumbkopf like our photographer, who once broke the grip frame of a 6946 forcing its housing pin back into place. Watch Mr. Furlette’s video. These grips are not easy to find. We have never had more than 20 pair at one time, ever. These are long discontinued. As the old song goes, that’s all there is and there ain’t no more. We’re offering the grips in the photos, or their identical mates from the same batch, each pair for only $ 49.00.

title: For Sale:  WW2 & Vintage Bayonets & Knives
location: Central NJ, New Jersey, United States
postcontent:
Up for sale are 5 bayonets/knives.  The 3 bayonets date back to WW2 or just post WW2.  I believe the MK2 KaBar is also from that period but I cannot say for sure, and I am uncertain of the Camillus's age.  

Os so here we go:

The top knife is a very well used Camillus fighting knife.  Stamped US and Camillus underneath.

Underneath is another fighting knife.  Stamped KaBar on one side of the hilt, and MK2 on the other.  Comes in a leather sheath.  Based on what I could find about MK2 knives I believe this to be WW2 era.

M4 Bayonet with sheath marked USM4 PAL.  If you look up the markings these are quite rare and go for quite a bit of money.  This one is in good condition and comes with it's sheath.

M4 Bayonet with sheath marked Kiffe Japan.  This is another somewhat rare bayonet, as it was made for the M1 but was not issued to US troops.  Again a quick search will turn up that these go for a good chunk of change and are collectable.  This one again is in good condition with its sheath.

The last bayonet is an M5 marked USM5 Imperial.  I believe this one dates to sometime in the 50's but I am not certain.  Bayonet is in good shape, comes with the sheath.  

Any questions feel free to ask.  Armslist only allows me to put up 3 pics, if you want a pic of anything specific just let me know.

Pickup in Ocean Gate or Tinton Falls.

$300 for all 5 knives
